{{Greek myth (nymph)}}
'''Aegle''' ({{lang-grc|Αἴγλη}} "brightness" or "dazzling light") is the name of several different figures in [[Greek mythology]]:
*Aegle, one of the daughters of [[Asclepius]] by [[Epione]], according to the [[Suda]]<ref>[[Suda]], ''s.v.'' {{lang|grc|Ἠπιόνη}}</ref> or by [[Lampetia]],<ref>[[Pliny the Elder]], ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Naturalis Historia]]'' 35. 40. § 31</ref> the daughter of the Sun, according to [[Hermippus]],.<ref>[[Hermippus]], in [[Scholia]] in [[Aristophanes]], ''Plutos'' 701</ref>  Her name is said to have derived from "Αἴγλη" ("Aegle"), meaning "Brightness," or "Splendor," either from the beauty of the human body when in good health, or from the honor paid to the medical profession.<ref>{{Citation  | last = Greenhill  | first = William Alexander  | contribution = Aegle (5)  | editor-last = Smith  | editor-first = William  | title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]  | volume = 1  | pages = 27  | place = Boston  | year = 1867  | contribution-url = http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0036.html }}</ref>
*Aegle, the most beautiful of the [[Naiad]]s, daughter of [[Zeus]] and [[Neaera (Greek mythology)|Neaera]],<ref>[[Virgil]], ''[[Bucolics|Eclogues]]'' 6. 20</ref> by whom [[Helios]] begot the [[Charites]].<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], 9. 35. § 1</ref>
*Aegle, one of the [[Heliades]], a sister of [[Phaethon|Phaeton]], and daughter of [[Helios]] and [[Clymene (mythology)|Clymene]].<ref>[[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus]], ''Fabulae'' 154, 156</ref>  In her grief at the death of her brother she and her sisters were changed into [[Populus|poplar]]s.
*Aegle, one of the [[Hesperides]].<ref>''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'' 2. 5. § 11</ref><ref>[[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]] on ''[[Aeneid]]'' 4. 484</ref>
*Aegle, daughter of [[Panopeus (mythology)|Panopeus]], who was beloved by [[Theseus]], and for whom he forsook [[Ariadne]].<ref>[[Plutarch]], ''[[Theseus]]'' 20</ref><ref>[[Athenaeus]], ''Banquet of The Learned'', 13. p. 557</ref><ref>{{Citation  | last = Schmitz  | first = Leonhard  | contribution = Aegle (1), (2), (3) and (4)  | editor-last = Smith  | editor-first = William  | title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]  | volume = 1  | pages = 27  | place = Boston  | year = 1867  | contribution-url = http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0036.html }}</ref>

