'''Manuel Antonio Acevedo''' (1770 – 1 October 1825) was an [[Argentina|Argentine]] statesman, lawyer and priest. He was a representative to the [[Congress of Tucumán]] which on 9 July 1816 [[Argentine Declaration of Independence|declared the Independence of Argentina]].

Acevedo was born in [[Salta]] and studied in [[Córdoba, Argentina|Córdoba]], following an ecclesiastical career at the [[Montserrat School]]. He was ordained a priest on 8 December 1794 and served in [[Cachi, Argentina|Cachi]], then [[Molinos, Salta|Molinos]] in [[Salta Province]], and later in [[Belén, Catamarca|Belén]], [[Catamarca Province]].

In 1815 Acevedo was elected by [[San Fernando del Valle de Catamarca|Catamarca]] to the [[Tucumán Congress]] and served in 1816 for the declaration. He supported the idea of a constitutional [[Inca]]n monarchy. After the Congress moved to Buenos Aires, he served as president of the body. He then returned to his parish in Belén. In 1824 he again represented Catamarca in the General Congress.

