[[File:Maqam Ibrahim, Makkah.jpg|thumb|upright|The structure containing the ''Maqām'']]
The '''''Maqām Ibrāhīm''''' ({{lang-ar|مَـقَـام إِبْـرَاهِـيْـم|lit=Station of Abraham}})<ref name="Cite quran|2|125|e=197|s=ns">{{cite quran|2|125|e=197|s=ns}}</ref><ref name="Cite quran|3|97|t=y|s=ns">{{Cite quran|3|97|t=y|s=ns}}</ref> is a stone associated with [[Abraham in Islam|Abraham]], [[Ishmael in Islam|Ishmael]] and their rebuilding of the ''[[Kaaba|Ka‘bah]]'' in what is now the [[Great Mosque of Mecca]] in [[Saudi Arabia]]. According to Islamic tradition, the [[petrosomatoglyph|imprint on the stone]] came from Abraham's feet.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Hajj |first=F.E. |last=Peters |chapter=Another Stone: The Maqam Ibrahim |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EK5MqskDYC0C&pg=PA16 |place=Princeton, New Jersey |publisher=Princeton University Press |date=1994 |pp=16–17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/989361/saudi-arabia|title=Maqam-e-Ibrahim shines ... like visitors’ faith|date=25 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref> According to one tradition it appeared when Abraham stood on the stone while building the Kaaba; when the walls became too high, Abraham stood on the ''maqām'', which miraculously rose up to let him continue building and also miraculously went down in order to allow Ishmael to hand him stones. Other traditions held that the footprint appeared when the wife of Ishmael washed Abraham's head, or alternatively when Abraham stood atop it in order to summon the people to perform the pilgrimage to Mecca.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |first=M.J. |last=Kister |title=Maḳām Ibrāhīm |p=105 |encyclopedia=The Encyclopaedia of Islam |volume=VI (Mahk-Mid) |edition=2nd |editor-last=Bosworth |publisher=Brill |year=1991}}</ref>
